rememberedPersonSummary.name: Helen Hackett
story:
We would like to thank Macmillan Cancer Support for all of their work, from when Helen was first ill and treated, through to support from their palliative care nurses, and carer support.

Macmillan has experienced huge funding losses recently, and needs our support to continue delivering their essential services. Without Macmillan, the support offered to cancer patients would suffer, including practical, emotional and family support.

Please help us to support their work and donate what you can in memory of Helen.

Simon, Jasmine, Rosa and Sam

story:
My grandmother was looked after by Macmillan nurses before she sadly passed away a number of years ago from cancer which she battled and beat a number of times over 20/30 years until she passed.

And now a family friend is being cared for, the woman in question Lizzie tovey is a partially sighted/blind runner who has completed many marathons etc over the last few years all whilst with cancer too but raising thousands of pounds in the process. She is now Unable to run anymore due to her condition worsening and I wish to now complete a number of marathons on her behalf. Starting with the Edinburgh on may 2021 I’m also signed up to do the London marathon in October 2021.

I say run a marathon but being ex military I will be looking to carry it out as a TAB (tactical advance to battle) wearing military trousers, boots, and whilst carrying a burgen weight of 40lbs as feel this would then be more of test. Though taking longer to compete I feel it is more suited to myself and would mean abit more than just running alone and in trainers.

Aiming for a time of sub 4hrs & 30-45mins and training will start in the new year 

Every penny helps so please give where you can and thank you x

story:
No parent ever wants to be told their child has cancer. But when they are, as they are every single day, having somebody there to support you is more valuable than can be put into words.

Our son Maxwell has Hodgkin Lymphoma. We're fortunate. This is a curable disease, and the treatment has an extremely high success rate. There are so many parents out there who would love to be in our position. But we still rely on help and support from our Macmillan nurse, who has been with us every step of the way from first diagnosis.

Maxwell has been through a tough time, and there is more yet to come. So far, we've found it tougher than he has. He's an absolute trooper.

pageSummary: Raising money, awareness on behalf of Lisa Jackson because She's simply inspirational x
pageSummaryWhat: Raising money, awareness on behalf of Lisa Jackson
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for supporting our fundraising.  Instead of spending money on sending Christmas Cards this year why not leave a message for your colleagues and leave a donation instead for Macmillan Cancer Support.  It is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.     

Lisa was diagnosed with Acute Myeloid Leukaemia in June 2020, after a visit to her GP as her 17yr old son had found her on the floor at home.  She was sent to Colchester Hospital for tests, a treatment plan was pulled together and Lisa was transferred to St Bartholomew's Hospital in London. She received her first session of chemotherapy followed by three more cycles.  Lisa came home on 3rd Dec from hospital after her fourth round of Chemo. On the 29th Nov Lisa said 'I feel really well, I've got energy, an appetite, I'm sleeping like a baby & I've got a nice little boy hairstyle with natural highlights that's growing back daily, I'm so happy with it'.   Lisa has got so much love for the hospital, the nurses and the doctors who have cared for her.  Through her journey she has kept such positiveness and with her daily facebook blog has cheered all of us up with her witty commentary of life in a hospital bed attached to 'Metal Mickey'.

I asked her personally if we could donate some money to any charity which one would it be?  Lisa nominated Macmillan, in her words ' they have helped me so much and gone above & beyond getting me firm guidance to help me with everything else going on in my life whilst I put on my big girls knickers & fight AML. They literally explored every avenue for me giving me peace of mind all the way, I cant thank them enough'.

Therefore by Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.  Just think how much a few pounds could go to help.

eventName: In memory of Elizabeth Ann Wykes
pageSummary: Remembering an Inspirational Lady because they provided such excellent care for Mum
pageSummaryWhy: they provided such excellent care for Mum
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Elizabeth Ann Wykes
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page, mum slipped away peacefully on the 24th November 2020 after an 18 month battle with cancer, sadly this was one she could not fight any longer, our family are beyond heartbroken and have lost a truly amazing wife, mother, sister, grandma, aunt and friend.

From the diagnosis through to the end, through countless set backs, she never complained once, she took every day in her stride with dignity and positivity, in the last few weeks she was thinking of us, sorting Christmas presents for everyone with her sister, making arrangements so my dad did not have added stress, making us so proud.  Mum and Dad were absolutely besotted with each other, even though completely different people, her love of shopping, musicals and dad an army man with his shooting and fishing, yet it worked and resulted in 51 years of marriage still going strong.   Family was everything to mum.

Due to restrictions so many could not attend Mums' funeral on the 9th December and flowers were just family, so many have asked to make donations so felt easier for us to set up this page.

Macmillan have been an absolute godsend, Helen and the team at NGH, the Doctors, Palliative and District Nurses.  They did so much for our family and we are so grateful, when mum had to go for appointments and Dad was not allowed to attend,  Macmillan went with her, when anything wasn't clear, Macmillan explained, I cannot put into words how much they helped so please support an amazing cause xx

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Throughout this troubling year, the day to day concern for many people around the world has been the profound impact of COVID-19 and the effect is has had on the lives of many. There is no question that the effect of this pandemic will have repercussions for years to come, while the world takes time to heal and find some normality again after such a life altering year.

However, there is one disease that many still face on a daily basis that remains as prevalent as ever, one that people have been fighting for years and will continue to fight against for many years to come, thats impact will be felt by not only themselves but those around them. Cancer.

For the majority of people there is a chance that either someone they care for, or they themselves, will encounter this grievous disease in their lifetime. 

For those already undergoing treatment in 2020 life has become more challenging than ever, what with the increased health risk due to the current pandemic and the impact it has had on cancer related treatment, including delays in treatments and cancellations of routine screenings. As well as this, an estimated 50,000 people have been left undiagnosed, with analysis showing that it could take as long as 20 months to clear the backlog in cancer diagnosis. As a whole, this has been a year that will not be without consequences

It is because of this that we are starting off 2021 by raising money for Macmillan Cancer Support - a leading charity in the field of cancer related treatment/care that provides an abundance of support for both cancer patients and their families all over the country every single year, especially during the intense strain brought upon by COVID in 2020.

All and any donations received tonight will go directly to Macmillan.

eventName: I'm going to go on a long, long walk for my dad
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
My dad is my hero. 

Recently he was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer, which we thought had been found early enough to have surgery and be removed.
This was a hard pill to swallow in itself, but there was a lot of hope and we felt if this was the case, he would be okay and get back to normal.

Sadly, the situation has changed in the past week and we're now in a situation where time is going to be limited. 

I love my dad, and I love my family. He's a father, a grandfather and a fantastic role model. 
My son, Oliver adores him and vice versa. My family will not be the same without him and he doesn't deserve what's happening to him. 

I want to try and raise some money for charity, so that other people don't lose loved ones to this horrible disease in the future. It's not much - but I want to do something.  

I will go for a long walk in the dales of Yorkshire. 10 miles to start with. I haven't even planned a route yet - but I will. I live very close to the Yorkshire Moors, so it'll start and end there. I'll do this on January the 25th 2021.

story:
Thank you for supporting my fundraising!

At the end of January, I'll be 'braving the shave' to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support and having all my hair cut/shaved off. In my opinion, there's nothing brave about what I'm doing. It's my choice to do this and I'm fortunate enough to make that choice, knowing that it will grow back quickly. Millions of people suffering from cancer do not have that choice. Macmillan Cancer Support is there to help everyone who is impacted by cancer live life as fully as they can, providing financial, physical and emotional support. I'm so proud to be supporting Macmillan as our chosen charity for the Franklin Templeton London and Leeds offices. 

I'll also be donating my hair to a charity (TBC), helping to support children suffering from cancer.

Please give generously for this amazing cause!

Charlotte xx

story:
So here’s something a little bit different and not something you’d expect from me as I’m a fat lad, not a fit lad....

10 and a bit years ago my Dad died of heart failure after suffering with Endocarditis, and I know of lots of other people, or their family members, who have also had issues with their hearts - and without a heart, your pretty much knackered!

When I saw this on a friends timeline, I thought I’d have a pop at it. It’s to do 100km between Boxing Day and the end of January; For your health, For the Challenge, For the cause! It’s to help out a great charity and to improve health and well being and welcoming 2021 with new healthy habits. 

So, let’s have a pop at this and support a great cause, and a raise a little bit of money... I’m not asking for loads, just the cost of a pint or two at the bar whether that be in town, at football, at the racetrack, or on the rally field - every little bit helps.

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Edith Lintern
story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate £12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

	Set up your own fundraiser on this page

eventName: TelecomTV Great Big Telecoms Quiz of the Year - Guide Dogs UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Following on from our successful charity pinball tournament in 2019, TelecomTV will continue to donate to our chosen charities of choice, the National Autistic Society, and Guide Dogs UK through various promotions and offers throughout the year.

Guide Dogs UK

As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

eventName: Dave Kent's Name A Puppy Bonzo
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Dave:

We all know that dogs are pretty amazing creatures, talented, often funny, sometimes serious but overall gifted with their own individuality. Now, just imagine that you are totally blind and need the support and expertise of one of these precious animals to lead you across the mouth of Oxford Street. Perhaps you might need to use the underground to get to work or travel across the Pennines to see your Gran. Now imagine that you are achieving all of this with the support of a brilliant four-legged mobility operative.

Over the last 40+ years, I’ve been lucky enough to be partnered with these incredible creatures. The sense of weaving through the underground or walking along the street without fear is just mind-blowing, and all because this four-legged, fur-covered fabulousness is right by your side, keeping you safe and on track. I’ve had this privilege for over half my life and am passionate that other people in a similar boat to me receive the same care, love and attention that I’ve received by one of the finest charities active on the planet today.

For other people to enjoy the same love, attention and support I’ve
received, please give generously to the Bonzo name-a-puppy appeal. Not only would you be giving a few of your coppers to a brilliant charity, you would be allowing another vision impaired person or child to take their first steps in the world with a friendship that only grows from strength to strength and really does change a life. I know, because mine was.

Thank you for your faultless ongoing support and I know that, between us all, we can pull together to allow someone else to have a slice of the good stuff with Wendy, Hevan, Melthorne or, best of all, Bonzo.

John:

Having spent time with Dave, it has become so clear to me what an amazing blessing his dog, Chad is to him. Having written our song "Together We Shine" to raise awareness for Guide Dogs UK, we both thought it would be wonderful if we could help someone else receive the same love and support that Chad gives to Dave. Working with the existing Guide Dogs UK "Name A Puppy" scheme, which gives support to puppies in their Guide Dog training, we are hoping to raise enough money to train a guide dog, and name it "Bonzo" which is a  name very close to my heart.

With much love,

John, Dave, and not forgetting the one and only Chad (he’s the one, he’s the boy like thousands of others)

cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Let's Unite the World this Christmas
pageSummary: Listen to our song, enjoy and please donate because they gave my Uncle Mark the help he needed most :)
pageSummaryWhat: Listen to our song, enjoy and please donate
pageSummaryWhy: they gave my Uncle Mark the help he needed most :)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hi! My name's Sarah and I'm singing a very special song written by my Uncle Mark. He wrote this song to share a little hope this Christmas, and in order to raise money for those less fortunate.

Video URL: https://youtu.be/Ee9tJBPXEwA

When Mark became registered blind, the charity Guide Dogs provided him with the help he needed most; his first guide dog Lucy, who has since sadly passed, and his second Polly, have both given him his life back - a guide dog is a companion and most importantly, they are a lifeline. Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

Please donate, and help us to make a difference :)

story:
Im geeking out for GOSH and taking on a gaming challenge to raise money for the seriously ill children,  their families and the NHS staff at Great Ormond Street Hospital. 

As GOSH plays a role in the national response to the COVID-19 crisis by treating more children from hospitals across London, resources will become increasingly stretched.   

The hospital needs the support of Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity) now more than ever, so it can continue to deliver the best, life-saving care for seriously ill children. 

Your support will help keep me going when things get tough and give me the power-up I need to complete this challenge. Its quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the give now button on the right.

story:
4 years ago I donated 15 inches of my hair to the Little Princess Trust who make wigs for boys and girls with cancer who have lost their hair and I ended up raising over £500. 2 years later when my hair grew back I did it again. 

However, this year is the most special to me. 2020 has made me realise how blessed I really am. I've learnt to appreciate everyone and everything. In a months time I will once again be donating my hair to the Little Princess Trust and but this time raising money for Cancer Research UK!

I encourage you all to do something good this Christmas, no matter how small. A lot of charities need your help and a few others close to my heart are: The Fire Fighters Charity, Great Ormond Street Hospital and Kidney Research UK. 

Thank you so much for your donation! 

Merry Christmas xx

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Marie Curie is the UK’s leading end of life charity.  They provide frontline nursing and hospice care, a free support line and a wealth of information and support on all aspects of dying, death and bereavement.  In these uncertain times, raising money to help our local nurses makes such a difference. Every penny means they can provide more care – at home and in our hospices. The money we raise is desperately needed at the moment as coronavirus has forced the Marie Curie team to cancel many of their fundraising activities. 

Marie Curie is a charity that's very close to our hearts here at The Kitchen, as Kate explains: "My mum was diagnosed with stage 4 ovarian cancer in 2014.  She had around three years of treatment and also developed Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma before receiving a terminal diagnosis.  My sister and I were able to nurse her at home during her final illness and this meant so much to mummy and to us as a family.  In the final 3 weeks of her life we had support every night from the nurses at Marie Curie.  They didn't just care for mummy, they cared for us all.  They calmed our fears, allowed us to rest and provided so much comfort to us all during those lonely night-time hours.  They truly were our angels. 

So this Christmas at The Kitchen, we are holding a virtual Raffle Extravaganza to raise money for this wonderful cause.  

We have a great selection of 15+ prizes to be won, including hampers and vouchers from many of our local businesses. Along with each prize, each winner will receive a £20 Kitchen voucher as well.  These prizes will be shared on our social media pages over the coming days and the draw will take place on Tuesday 22nd December! 

Tickets are priced at 1 for £2, 3 for £5 or 6 for £10 and can be purchased in The Kitchen or by making a donation to this page - we will email you your ticket number(s) within 48 hours of entry.   Please remember to leave your name in the optional 'Your Name' box so that we can contact you should you be one of our lucky winners! You will still have the option to 'Hide' your name from public view should you wish. 

Thank you for supporting this wonderful cause,

The Kitchen Team xx
title: Raffle Extravaganza in aid of Marie Curie

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Sheena  Brady
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

2020 the year that wan't. No race for life, no Glasgow Santa Dash and SO many events cancelled and charities are struggling. So I have decided to do my own event and will don the RED and will be running around Rutherglen and Burnside on Sunday 13th December. I have chosen to try a little fundraising for Marie Curie as they kindly looked after Sheena our lovely, mum. So if I can help them a little to help others... any wee contributions greatly received. Stay safe, stay well. xx

story:
This terrible year has touched all of us.  We have worked hard, persevered and it has been a triumph for the Commercialisation Office with successes in every team. 
Our Christmas party will be an odd one with no Secret Santa and an on-line party.  It’s also a time to remember that we are the lucky ones. 
Thank you for donating the money you would have spent on Secret Santa to Marie Curie – helping people dying at home this winter: https://www.mariecurie.org.uk/

RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

pageSummary: We are raising money in memory of Morton because he was always an avid supporter of water safety.
pageSummaryWhat: We are raising money in memory of Morton
pageSummaryWhy: he was always an avid supporter of water safety.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Morton Wilson
story:
We have set up this page in loving memory of Morton, who was a much loved husband, dad, grandad, friend  and coach and mentor to many. As many of you will know, Morton sadly passed away on the 3rd of December and is greatly missed, but fondly remembered. We have chosen to raise funds for the RNLI as he was an avid supporter of water safety, spending many years volunteering at the local swimming club, chester city life saving club, teaching swimming and water safety to many. Any donation you are able to make will be go towards helping in saving lives in the future.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Jenny Wevell
story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

Your support is much appreciated.

Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.name: WWF-UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Sightsavers' vision is of a world where no one is blind from avoidable causes and where visually impaired people participate equally in society.
charity.name: Sightsavers
owner: Lifelong Learning Centre University of Leeds
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Time for us to burn off those festive pounds and turn them into pounds for charity....

Staff at the Lifelong Learning Centre at University of Leeds have decided to individually run every day in January. Rain or shine, sleet and snow.

We will be logging our runs, sharing our routes, our stories, our highs and our lows all in aid of the wonderful charity Sightsavers. They

work to eliminate avoidable blindness and promote the rights
of people with disabilities

Feel free to simply cheer us on and show us some moral support but if you are able to give an amount no matter how small to reward our chosen charity for our efforts then of course we will be very grateful.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.
title: 31 Days of Running in January

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
eventName: Let's Unite the World this Christmas
pageSummary: Listen to our song, enjoy and please donate because no child should ever be at risk.
pageSummaryWhat: Listen to our song, enjoy and please donate
pageSummaryWhy: no child should ever be at risk.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hi! My name's Sarah and I'm singing a very special song written by my Uncle Mark. He wrote this song to share a little hope this Christmas, and in order to raise money for those less fortunate.

Video URL: https://youtu.be/Ee9tJBPXEwA

UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund) is a United Nations agency which provides humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. No child should ever feel alone or be at risk.

Please donate, and help us to make a difference :)

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hello Space Marines!

Thank you for taking the time to visit one of our JustGiving pages! We're taking part in a 12-day long festive stream from the 12th-23rd December!

Every little helps and the money you donate goes straight to your chosen charity! You've chosen to donate to Médecins Sans Frontières, aka. Doctors Without Borders, ( https://www.msf.org/ ) an organisation dedicated to providing medical assistance to people affected by conflict, epidemics, disasters, or exclusion from healthcare. You can read more about this life-changing charity via the link provided!

You can check out our stream at ( twitch.tv/fragsoc ) and donations will be open from 2pm on Saturday 12th!
title: UoY's 12 Days Of Fragmas

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I did it last year, I struggled but I did It!! I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
